Main culprit Putin
Moscow-based German, French, and Swedish medical experts agree that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the Novichok nerve agent. Navalny is Russia's President Putin's largest opponent and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
It's worth noting that due to Navalny surviving, the relations between Russia and Germany have not deteriorated.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced that Navalny is "a victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her eyes, the incident was very serious, and only the Russian government could and must respond.
She emphasizes that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to launch an independent and transparent investigation.
The European Union and the United Kingdom also support this appeal.
If the investigation results prove that the Russian government is the mastermind behind the incident, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless of what is said, according to the regulations of the prohibition of chemical weapons, poisoning is a prohibited behavior.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the Novichok nerve agent to deal with its political opponents.
Sergei Skripal, a former Russian double agent, and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil in 2018.
Both of them survived and hid.
The Kremlin has strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov firmly asserted that "there is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service chief Sergei Naryshkin even said this is the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, using it to blame the credibility of the Russian government.
Narezkii's claim is clearly an exaggeration, but he also revealed a fact: the Navalny affair has harmed Russia more than helped it.
Before the upcoming election, it is unthinkable that he would poison a famous political rival, and the poison used was a product developed by the former Soviet Union.
Especially at a time when the people of neighboring Belarus were protesting the August elections, this timing is particularly noteworthy.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to Navalny's case was particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If it is indeed the Russian government, as the Germans claimed, this murder would also be a failed operation.
Putin has long been the Darth Vader of the international arena, intervening in the US elections, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK out of the EU, and propping up Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he was shrewd, far-sighted and cunning.
Why can't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why Navalny could escape to Germany, and was soon diagnosed as being poisoned.
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream pipeline to Germany is facing cancellation.
This murder clearly did not justify the cost.
In fact, this has only stirred up more public opposition to Russia's authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin's doing, the claim that the West's intelligence agencies were responsible is even more outlandish.
If such accusations are true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have spoken out about the truth of the nerve agent Novichok.
More might come from a plot hatched by Putin's inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needs Navalny to shut up before the election, or maybe it's trouble caused by his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade neurotoxins.
Putin's political thugs, though loyal, are incredibly stupid, and they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, only a minority of those involved knew the truth.
Other failed poisonings share similar characteristics: the 2015 and 2017 poisonings of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza, who is a coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Open Investigation Committee.
In 2018, the outlet's founder Peter Verzilov was poisoned.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russian judicial abuses.
It can be traced further back to 2006, the poisoning of former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko. Alexander Litvinenko often criticized Russia's security agencies.
Just like the Navalny case, such poisoning often backfires.
In 2004, liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta columnist Anna Politkovskaya was poisoned on a plane flying from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived, only to be gunned down two years later in the elevator of her apartment building.
As Putin said, her death has caused huge damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is no excuse for the Kremlin.
Regardless of whether Putin was personally involved, the system he created allowed such atrocities to occur. This system was both ineffective and useless, and it was a farce involving some shameless actors.
Navalny's death is what the Kremlin wants, and it's the ultimate goal for the lackeys to satisfy their master Putin.
Loyalty is the only goal in Putin's inner circle.
Even if they failed to poison, they would not be punished.
Because it's all for the president's benefit.
Those who might seek proof of poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless of what is said, the Kremlin is still the culprit.
Western countries must clearly take a stance, even if their own economy is affected, they still need to impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin created a system centered around Putin.
All responsibility for what happened in Russia falls on him.
